-- ICBC, Jinan Iron, Laiwu Steel, Sinopec, Wuhan Steel: China Equity Preview
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2010-12-13T18:37:41Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-13/icbc-jinan-iron-laiwu-steel-sinopec-china-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
 unusual  price changes in China trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and share prices are as of the last close.  The  Shanghai Composite Index , which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, gained 81.91, or 2.9 percent, to
2,922.95. The  CSI 300 Index  rose 3.1 percent to 3,261.06.  Banks: China is likely to set a target of at least 7
trillion yuan ($1.1 trillion) of new loans, according to two
people briefed on the matter. A quota of more than 7 trillion
yuan would exceed estimates made by UBS AG and Bank of America
Corp. in the past month, suggesting the government may avoid
stepping up a clampdown on lending.  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China Ltd.  (601398 CH): The
world’s largest lender by market value gained 1.2 percent to
4.28 yuan.  China Construction Bank Corp.  (601939 CH): The
nation’s second-largest lender gained 0.8 percent to 4.78 yuan.  China Oilfield Services Ltd.  (601808 CH): The unit of the
nation’s largest offshore oil producer was awarded a contract
for up to five years for its COSLPIONEER rig with Statoil ASA.
The shares soared by the 10 percent limit, rising to 24.74 yuan.  China Petroleum & Chemical Corp.  (600028 CH): Asia’s
largest oil refiner, known as Sinopec, may reduce 2011 oil-
processing volume growth to 8.4 percent as capacity expansion
slows, according to the Shandong-based industry portal
Oilchem.net. Sinopec’s oil processing will rise to about 4.4
million barrels a day. The shares advanced 3 percent to 8.36
yuan.  Jinan Iron & Steel Co.  (600022 CH) and  Laiwu Steel Corp. 
(600102 CH): The two companies controlled by Shandong Iron and
Steel Group have settled the details of a merger and will resume
trading today. Jinan gained 1.5 percent to 4.11 yuan on Sept. 7,
before trading was suspended. Laiwu gained 2 percent to 9.28
yuan on Sept. 7.  Wuhan Iron & Steel Co.  (600005 CH): The listed unit of
China’s third-biggest steelmaker received approval from the
China Securities Regulatory Commission for its rights offer. The
shares gained 2.7 percent to 4.62 yuan.  -- Zhang Shidong ,  Helen Sun . Editor:  Eric Martin   To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
